#Requirements #Engineering #AI #Human-Centered 

There has been more research on human-centric RE such as emotion, [8], [9], personality traits [10], [11] and dealing with mental and physical challenges [12]

limited research on RE for human-centric AI systems, and when evident, it only focused on ethics and explainability.

Google PAIR included six chapters: guidelines involved six chapters as following: User Needs, Data Collection + Evaluation, Mental Models, Explainability + Trust, Feedback + Control and Errors + Graceful Failure.

Apple’s human-interface guidelines: Provided a guide for developers when designing ML applications with a human-centric approach.

Guidelines for human-centric AI interaction: Amershi et al. [16] developed 18 guidelines for creating human- centric AI systems.

Both [25] and [20] presented the need to develop a modeling language to support RE4AI.

The aim is to look into the differ- ent RE modeling languages available such as Goal-Oriented Requirements Languages (GRL), KAOS Methodology [35], risk-oriented and i* model [36] and find one that fits into RE4AI.

One of the presenting challenges in current RE4AI is the lack of communication and a gap between data scientists and software engineers [17], [18].
